From sarah.goslee at gmail.com  Mon Jan 24 19:15:26 2011
From: sarah.goslee at gmail.com (Sarah Goslee)
Date: Mon, 24 Jan 2011 13:15:26 -0500
Subject: [R-sig-eco] lines() adds extra line
In-Reply-To: <AANLkTinPibmymdCjsak-2_73DY3OmG=GJrvo2NNebYxP@mail.gmail.com>
References: <AANLkTinPibmymdCjsak-2_73DY3OmG=GJrvo2NNebYxP@mail.gmail.com>
Message-ID: <AANLkTimTXE+EVzdgv7WCKrw1WNDYPNAUEwzpMVzg00XD@mail.gmail.com>

R is doing just as you asked. If you look at the middle of c(x, x) the
x values jump from 10 to -10 and R draws the line segment connecting
them, as it's been told.

> c(x,x)[195:205]
 [1]   9.4   9.5   9.6   9.7   9.8   9.9  10.0 -10.0  -9.9  -9.8  -9.7

You might rather have:
> x2.rev <- c(x, rev(x))
> x.rev.pred <- predict(lm(dataBoth.poly ~ x2.rev + I(x2.rev^2)+I(x2.rev^3)+I(x2.rev^4)+I(x2.rev^5)+I(x2.rev^6)))
> plot(x2.rev, x.rev.pred, type="l")

Sarah


